<subSubSection pageId="20" pageNumber="171" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="20.[151,1436,293,570]" pageId="20" pageNumber="171">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,503,401,426]" pageId="20" pageNumber="171">Distribution and habitat.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Cope, 1868" authorityName="Cope" authorityYear="1868" box="[513,741,401,426]" class="Reptilia" family="Gymnophthalmidae" genus="Loxopholis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="20" pageNumber="171" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="ferreirai">
<emphasis box="[513,741,401,426]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="171">Loxopholis ferreirai</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is endemic to the archipelago of Anavilhanas, lower 
<collectingRegion country="Uruguay" name="Rio Negro" pageId="20" pageNumber="171">Negro River</collectingRegion>
, state of 
<collectingRegion box="[316,437,438,462]" country="Brazil" name="Amazonas" pageId="20" pageNumber="171">Amazonas</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[448,516,437,462]" name="Brazil" pageId="20" pageNumber="171">Brazil</collectingCountry>
(
<figureCitation box="[532,616,437,462]" captionStart="FIGURE 12" captionStartId="20.[151,250,1552,1574]" captionTargetBox="[157,1428,633,1523]" captionTargetId="figure@20.[151,1436,625,1531]" captionTargetPageId="20" captionText="FIGURE 12. Distribution of examined material of Loxopholis ferreirai and Marinussaurus curupira." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/581987/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="171">Fig. 12</figureCitation>
). It represents a rare case of endemicity of a terrestrial vertebrate species to an archipelago or island in 
<taxonomicName box="[499,618,473,498]" class="Sordariomycetes" family="Meliolaceae" genus="Amazonia" kingdom="Fungi" order="Meliolales" pageId="20" pageNumber="195" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="genus">Amazonia</taxonomicName>
. 
<taxonomicName authority="Cope, 1868" authorityName="Cope" authorityYear="1868" box="[630,858,473,498]" class="Reptilia" family="Gymnophthalmidae" genus="Loxopholis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="20" pageNumber="171" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="ferreirai">
<emphasis box="[630,858,473,498]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="171">Loxopholis ferreirai</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is terrestrial and diurnal, inhabits the igapó forest present on the islands, where it is usually found in the leaf litter and under decomposing trunks and fallen palm leaves (personal communication with T. Ávila-Pires).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
